<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-193-098  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 193 098.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  March 2 1990 pA5(W) pA6(E) 10 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T top officials had strong gains in earnings for 1989; chairmanAllen's pay rose 36% to $1.74 million; union criticizes increases.andO;(Robert E. Allen)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Keller, John J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT and T had a strong year of increased earnings, and the companyreports that its top executives will have a nice pay raise to showfor it.andP;  The company's three top executives will make a combined$3.71 million for 1989, up 25 percent.andP;  AT and T chairman RobertE. Allen posts the largest gain, up 36 percent to $1.74 million.andO;In the wake of AT and T restructuring that cut some 25,000 workersfrom the pay roles over the past two years, with another 10,000 tofollow in 1990, union officials were less than enthusiastic aboutthe salary increases.andP;  Union officials complain that workers havesuffered from the belt tightening, but management has not carriedan equal amount of the burden.andP;  Compensation for AT and T's top 12executives now totals $13.46 million.andP;  AT and T had 1989 earningsof $2.69 billion; in 1988, the company reported a loss of $1.67billion, the result of a $6.72 billion charge in the 4th qtr.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (officials and employees).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     SalaryWagesTelephone CompaniesManagementTelecommunications.andO;Person:    Allen, Robert E. (salaries, etc.).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>